<link href="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/viewtopic.php?t=3328&amp;p=15509#p15509"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Oh no file overwritten.  Aye yai yai and worser words.]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/viewtopic.php?t=3328&amp;p=15509#p15509"><![CDATA[
Aye yai yai, I feel very terrible today.<br />Maybe it's happened to you as well.<br /><br />I started making text adjustments to an up and coming skin, <br />that I worked off and on for long time. I always made a copy after many changes, and put in a new folder.<br /><br />Big problem, big setback. <br />I made the adjustment on an older copy, by mistake. Then it saved the change to the last used location, <br />overwriting the most updated skin file, with a very old just modded file.<br />So I now lost everything I did for about a months work. Could not find any software that can undo an overwritten file. They only work for formatted or recycle bin files <img src="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/images/smilies/icon_mad.gif" alt=":x" title="Mad" />.  <br />So I learned something today. Making backup copies means nothing, <br />unless they are revised with alpha/numerics added, and even then,<br />switching between multiple skin files and saving with resource hacker, can still trip one up.<br />Have to really be aware where it's saving the file.  <br /><br />I'm going to use &quot;save all resources&quot; feature, so bitmaps and text files are separate from the skin file.<br />So if I'm sleepy or drunk, or just plain stupid, and screw up the wrong file, <br />I can assemble a new skin file relatively easily <img src="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/images/smilies/icon_e_wink.gif" alt=";)" title="Wink" /> <br /><br />Back to the drawing board.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=856">juniper7</a> — Wed Nov 05, 2014 8:36 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
